# TypeScript Standards

## Strict Rules (ESLint must block these)

```typescript
// ❌ any is forbidden
const data: any = fetch()

// ❌ floating promises
someAsyncFn()

// ❌ console.log — use the Pino logger
console.log('debug')

// ❌ hardcoded config values
const port = 3000
```

## Naming Conventions

| Construct | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Classes / Types / Interfaces | PascalCase | `OrderRepository` |
| Functions / variables | camelCase | `createOrder` |
| Constants | SCREAMING_SNAKE | `MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS` |
| Files | kebab-case | `order-repository.ts` |
| Folders | kebab-case | `use-cases/` |

## Entity Baseline Fields

Every domain entity must have:
```typescript
id: string        // ULID
tenantId: string
createdAt: Date
updatedAt: Date
deletedAt: Date | null   // soft delete only — never hard delete
version: number          // optimistic locking
```

## Value Objects

```typescript
// ✅ Immutable, validates on construction
class Email {
  private constructor(readonly value: string) {}
  static create(raw: string): Result<Email> {
    if (!raw.includes('@')) return fail(new DomainError('INVALID_EMAIL'))
    return ok(new Email(raw))
  }
}
```

## Error Handling

```typescript
// ✅ Structured errors with codes
throw new AppError('RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND', 'Order not found', 404, { orderId })

// ❌ Raw Error
throw new Error('not found')
```

## Forbidden Patterns

- `delete` on DB records — always set `deletedAt`
- Direct Prisma models returned from repositories — map to domain entities
- Tests that depend on execution order
- Tests without `beforeEach`/`afterEach` state cleanup
